<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en-GB">
  <!-- @import "../head" -->
  <!-- $activeArticles = nav-link--active -->
  <body>
    <!-- @import "../header" -->

    <main class="article-page deep-dive">
      <!-- BREADCRUMB -->
      <div class="breadcrumb">
        <span class="tag tag-red-light">DEEP DIVE</span>
        <span class="read-time-badge">12 MIN READ</span>
      </div>

      <!-- ARTICLE TITLE + AUTHOR -->
      <h1>Building a Design Token System from Scratch</h1>
      <div class="article-author">
        <img src="../assets/img/gui.avif" alt="Flashy" class="avatar" />
        <div class="article-author-info">
          <p class="author-name">By Guilherme</p>
          <p class="author-date">Published April 16, 2026</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TWO-COLUMN LAYOUT -->
      <div class="article-layout">
        <!-- MAIN CONTENT COLUMN -->
        <article class="article-content">
          <blockquote class="intro-quote">
            Design tokens are the atomic elements of your product's visual
            identity. Here is the step-by-step framework to transition from
            hard-coded hex values to a bulletproof token architecture that
            engineers will actually love using.
          </blockquote>

          <h2 id="1-namingConventions">1. Naming Conventions</h2>
          <p>
            The biggest mistake teams make is jumping straight into semantic
            tokens without defining the global scale first. Start with a neutral
            palette and establish a clear naming framework. We recommend the
            Category-Property-Concept-State format.
          </p>

          <pre class="code-block"><code>tokens.css


/* ❌ Bad: Too specific, hard to scale */
--color-button-blue-hover: #1D4ED8;
/* ✅ Good: Global →> Semantic */
--global-color-blue-500: #3B82F6;
--global-color-blue-600: #2563EB;
--semantic-color-primary-default: var(--global-color-blue-500);
--semantic-color-primary-hover: var(--global-color-blue-600);</code></pre>

          <h2 id="2-structuringTheFigmaFile">2. Structuring the Figma File</h2>
          <p>
            Keep your tokens isolated from your component library. Create a
            dedicated 'Foundations' file that publishes exclusively styles and
            variables.
          </p>

          <div class="video-embed">
            <img src="../assets/img/video-thumb.jpg" alt="Video thumbnail" />
          </div>

          <h2 id="3-handlingDarkMode">3. Handling Dark Mode</h2>
          <p>
            Dark mode should never require duplicating components. By mapping
            light and dark themes to the same semantic token names, the switch
            happens automatically at the variable level.
          </p>

          <blockquote class="pull-quote">
            "A token system isn't finished when it works in Figma. It's finished
            when a developer can build a new feature without ever sampling a
            color."
          </blockquote>

          <p>
            Take the time to align your variable collections with your
            codebase's theme provider. The initial setup takes hours, but it
            saves weeks of back-and-forth pixel pushing.
          </p>

          <div class="article-tags">
            <span>Figma</span>
            <span>PostScript</span>
            <span>Fonction</span>
            <span>InDesign Admin</span>
          </div>

          <!-- CTA BANNER -->
          <div class="article-cta">
            <h3>Found this useful?</h3>
            <p>Got a workflow hack of your own? Share it with the community.</p>
            <a href="../contact.html" class="btn btn-light">SUGGEST A TIP →</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- SIDEBAR -->
        <aside class="article-sidebar">
          <!-- TOC Widget -->
          <div class="sidebar-widget">
            <h4 class="sidebar-title">Article Guide</h4>
            <p class="sidebar-label">Quick Navigation</p>
